UML:TaggedValue.value:
Problems when requiring observation templates to be returned and used in GetResult requests:
- If GetResultTemplate returns a set of observation templates, this list can only be generated based upon the data that currently exists in the database. Each template should therefore only be valid during a interval of (sampling) time in the past. - A client could only request data in GetResult for one of these templates, so it would query the service for "data that matches the exact properties of the referenced observation (template)" - it would not query for "data that matches my previous filter criteria given in the GetResultTemplate request". - The client would not have a way to determine whether he has missed new data because of a property change in observation data that was not taken into account by the service at the time of creating the observation templates. The service would need to recognize this, but it would be quite difficult to implement.
- If GetResultTemplate returns only an identifier for the filter criteria of the client, the client could reference those criteria in later GetResult requests. The client would then get access to the actual observation template in the response of a GetResult request - either via a URL or by a handle (e.g. identifier) that can be used in a Get* operation (tbd) to retrieve the observation template. - By comparing given identifiers, the client could recognize that it already has the observation template for the data returned upon a subsequent GetResult request. - However, for this to work the service would need to reuse observation template identifiers and therefore would need to recognize which templates it can (or rather, has to) reuse in such a subsequent GetResult request. This would require a (deep) property comparison (that can only be sped up if all properties of the observation are actually given with unique ID) which would be quite demanding on servers.
response with the result template matching the request criteria

ResultTemplate really just provides view upon result structure of the sensor, i.e. of its outputs.
DataArray needs to contain time stamp for measurement data ... can we restrict the data array to incorporate that?
what about data encoding - with the DataArray the service can use one of the encodings available for SWE Common ... does it matter for the client which encoding is used? ... we can have a default encoding that should be used, or we can add a request parameter (e.g. via extension) with which the client can tell the service which encodings are ok for him (though then the service would need to tell the client which encodings it supports).
(pending discussion result from 07-10-09 telcon) <font color="#ff0000">1. we need to specify that data coming from one sensor may not be encoded in a different resultType for the same observedProperty (which should only happen when there is more than one offering that contains the same observedProperty for the same procedure - in that case the result type for the observed property could differ)</font> <font color="#ff0000"> </font><font color="#ff0000">2. the swe:DataArray in the GetResultTemplateResponse? shall contain a DataChoice? (!) as elementType, where each item contains the resultType structure for each retrieved observedProperty (indicated via definition attribute of SWE Common component contained in the field?); in addition it contains the encoding the service will use when GetResult is called. We need a choice instead of DataRecord? because values for observedProperties have not necessarily been estimated (measured/observed) for the same samplingTime</font>
